05922nam a22006735i 9780292763616DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211973txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927636167 a10.7560/7500432doi  a(DE-B1597)586980  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHN120.M6bB34eb 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a301.44/044/097212221 aBalán, Jorge, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMen in a Developing Society :bGeographic and Social Mobility in Monterrey, Mexico /cElizabeth Jelin, Jorge Balán, Harley Linwood Browning. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1973  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFIGURES -- tMAP -- tTABLES -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart One. Setting the Scene -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Development of Monterrey as an Industrial Center -- t3. Characteristics of Communities of Origin of Migrants to Monterrey -- tPart Two. The Life Histories -- t4. Community, Family of Origin, and Educational Attainment -- t5. Entry into the Labor Force and Early Work Experience -- t6. The Social and Economic Context of Migration to Monterrey -- t7. Marriage and Early Family Formation -- t8. Paths of Occupational Mobility -- t9. Older Men's Biographical Profiles and Sons' Prospects -- tPart Three. A Broader Perspective -- t10. The Process of Stratification -- t11. The Monterrey Mobility Pattern: Consequences and Prospects -- tAppendices -- tA. Technical Aspects of the Execution of the Monterrey and Cedral Surveys -- tB. The Securing and Processing of the Life Histories -- tC. The Monterrey Mobility Study -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe central objective of Men in a Developing Society is to show, as concretely as possible, how men experience a period of rapid economic development, particularly in the areas of migration, occupational mobility, and status attainment. It is based mainly on a sample of 1,640 men in Monterrey, Mexico, a large and rapidly growing manufacturing metropolis in northern Mexico with much in-migration, and a sample of 380 men in Cedral, San Luis Potosí, a small, economically depressed community with high rates of out-migration, much of it to Monterrey. The study of men in Monterrey is perhaps the most thorough one yet conducted of geographic and social mobility in a Latin American city. In part, this was possible because of the innovation of collecting complete life histories that record what each man was doing for any given year in the lay areas of residence, education, family formation, and work. These data permit the effective use of the concepts of life cycle and cohort analysis in the interpretation of the men's geographic and occupational mobility. The experience of the Monterrey men in adapting to the varied changes required by their mobility was not found to be as difficult as is often indicated in the social science literature on the consequences of economic development. In part this may be because Monterrey, in comparison with most other Latin American cities, has been unusually successful in its economic growth. The impact of migration also was lessened because most of the men had visited the city prior to moving there and many had friends or relatives in the city. The age of the migrants upon arrival in Monterrey made a significant difference in subsequent occupational mobility; those of nonfarm background who arrived before age 25 fared better than natives of the city. Although it appears that status inheritance in Monterrey is somewhat higher than in industrialized countries, a considerable proportion of men do move up the occupational ladder. And perhaps as important, the Monterrey men, whether or not they themselves are moving up, perceive the society as an open one. The very success of Monterrey's development created conditions that would bring about changes in the educational, economic, and cultural expectations of its inhabitants. Thus, paradoxically, the general satisfaction and the lack of group and class conflict in Monterrey over the previous decades may well have given rise to future dissatisfaction and conflict.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMigration, InternalzMexicozMonterrey. 0aMonterrey (Mexico)--Population. 0aOccupational mobility. 0aSocial mobilityzMexicozMonterrey. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aBrowning, Harley Linwood, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJelin, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75004340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292763616423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292763616/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK